Section 4    FIBROMYALGIA: A HOLISTIC APPROACH 
                 by Andrea Lemieux, RNCP 
                mailto:newvital@istar.ca

         Read about Andrea Lemieux on our Meet the Team 
             page; http://www.Life-Choices.com/team.html 

A person who hurts everywhere, joints, bones, muscles, tendons, 
may be given any number of labels for their symptoms: arthritis, 
rheumatism, lumbago, polymyalgia rheumatica, gout, ankylosing 
spondylitis, and fibromyalgia. 

To diagnose fibromyalgia, doctors need to find sensitivity in at 
least 11 out of 18 itender points.i These areas, all where muscles 
attach to ligaments or bones, will exhibit pain with just the pressure 
of a thumb. People who have it suffer from pain day in and day 
out, all over their bodies -- plus fatigue, anxiety and depression. 
Other disorders such as hepatitis, Lyme disease, anemia, arthritic 
conditions, and depression, must be ruled out before a firm 
diagnosis of fibromyalgia can be made. 

Fibromyalgia and chronic fatigue syndrome are closely associated 
with one another. Both seem to begin after an infection or severe 
physical or emotional shock. In chronic fatigue, the patient will 
feel fatigue most; in fibromyalgia, the dominant symptom will be 
muscular pain. 

Fibromyalgia commonly occurs with other conditions, such as 
allergies, anxiety, toxicity, candida, PMS, irritable bowel 
syndrome, and viral infections. For the successful treatment of 
this often debilitating condition, a holistic approach is essential. 

As improbable as it may seem to the sufferer, the best 
recommendation is a steady program of moderate aerobic 
exercise. Without exercise, there will rarely be any improvement. 
It will be difficult, but the patient must push themselves to do it. 
They must start slowly, only three to five minutes a day, and pick 
exercises that do not use the most painful muscles. Gradually 
increase to 20 to 30 minutes three or more days a week. The 
methods of exercise best suited to fibromyalgia patients are 
said to be cycling (static cycle), walking, or swimming. 

Stress seems to be a major factor in this disease, relaxation 
techniques such as meditation, progressive relaxation and 
breathing exercises are critical. 

Nutrition is most important; the following recommendations 
will make an enormous difference in overcoming this condition. 
* Eat a high-fibre diet including six or more servings of 
vegetables daily; green vegetables are of prime importance. 
* Make sure your diet includes protein at most meals. Fish, 
poultry, and raw nuts and seeds in particular. Protein is 
necessary for maintenance and repair of all tissues in the body. 
* Eat four or five small meals daily to keep a steady supply of 
protein and carbohydrates available for proper muscle function. 
If the body does not have enough fuel for energy, it will rob the 
muscles of essential nutrients, causing muscle wasting and pain. 
* Do not eat red meat, dairy products, or any other foods that 
are high in saturated fats. Saturated fats promote inflammation 
and increase pain; also avoid fried food and rancid fats and oils 
of all kinds. 
* Avoid polyunsaturated vegetable oils like safflower, sunflower, 
soy, corn, and sesame, and oils that have been refined or made 
saturated by the process of hydrogenation, such as margarine, 
and manufactured mayonnaise and salad dressings. The fats that 
will reduce inflammation are in cold water fish, raw nuts and 
seeds, flaxseed oil and ground, raw flaxseeds. Extra-virgin olive 
oil is also a healthy and acceptable oil. 
* Avoid processed foods and white flour products such as bread 
and pasta. 
* Avoid caffeine, alcohol, and sugar. These substances enhance 
fatigue, increase muscle pain, and can interfere with normal sleep 
patterns. 
* Drink eight glasses of pure water daily. Herbal tea can be a part 
of this intake. A plentiful intake of liquids is important for flushing 
out toxins. 
* Investigate the possibility that food allergies and/or sensitivities 
may be contributing to the situation. Dairy and wheat allergies are 
particularly implicated in many cases of fibromyalgia and similar 
conditions. 

There are many supplements and physical therapies that are 
beneficial to fibromyalgia patients. It is important to work 
closely with a health care practitioner to find ways to gently 
detoxify the patient, while at the same time supporting and 
helping him or her to relieve the pain. Acupuncture or 
electroacupuncture has an excellent track record in treating 
pain.  Magnesium has long been considered helpful because 
it promotes muscle relaxation. Magnesium is available in nuts, 
legumes, whole grains, and dark green vegetables. Malic 
Acid has also been found useful in treating this condition. 
Malic Acid is naturally present in apples. 
 
Below is an especially delicious recipe for baked apples. 
The malic acid in apples will not only benefit the person 
with fibromyalgia, but it will also remedy indigestion 
because it inhibits fermentation and the growth of disease- 
producing bacteria in the digestive tract. 

